# Spec 0026 ‚Äî Optical Constructor UI (element/ray model, top‚Äëdown table, ribbon shell, groups, EN/RU)

This spec realises the Optical Constructor feature list: a new top‚Äëdown
operator‚Äëfacing constructor screen, layered on top of the existing
Avalonia + FuncUI (Elm‚Äëstyle MVU) desktop app, that reuses the existing
beam‚Äëtree physics, units, JSON storage, and snapshot undo/redo rather than
re‚Äëinventing them. The screen becomes the application's front door; the
present dockable‚Äëpanel main screen is preserved behind a *Legacy* menu
entry.

The spec is ordered by priority. The element/ray/geometry domain model and
the top‚Äëdown rendering surface are the conceptual heart of the tool and
gate every other part, so they come first and are marked **CRITICAL ‚Äî
land first**.

---

## 0. Binding constraints (apply to every part)

0.1 **Reuse the engine, do not re‚Äëtype it.** The constructor MUST drive the
existing beam tree (`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Domain/BeamTree.fs:35`
defines `ConstructorElement`; `:53` defines `BeamNode`; `:91` `solve`;
`:117` `routeAndSolve`) and the project aggregate
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Domain/Project.fs:26`,
`OpticalConstructorProject`). It MUST NOT introduce a parallel element
catalogue, a parallel solver, or a parallel project type.

0.2 **Canonical SI everywhere.** Every stored physical magnitude (table
dimensions, placement‚Äëpoint coordinates, distances along rays, box
dimensions) MUST be held in canonical SI base units (meters), matching the
units spine (`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Domain/Units.fs:20`,
`UnitOfMeasure`; `:43` `toMeters`; `:71` `fromMeters`). Unit conversion
happens ONLY at the display / import / export boundary through that module;
no other module hand‚Äërolls a conversion. Each element and the table MAY
carry a per‚Äëobject preferred display unit (display metadata only, mirroring
`BeamNode.defaultUnit`, BeamTree.fs:59).

0.3 **Pure, serializable MVU models; public FuncUI surface only.** All new
view models MUST be pure and serializable F# values (no Avalonia handle,
renderer instance, or cancellation token in a model), matching the existing
root model (`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/Shell.fs:94`,
`RootModel`). All view code MUST be authored against the public MIT
`Avalonia.FuncUI` NuGet DSL surface used today. The audit‚Äëgated FuncUI clone
at `C:/GitHub/Avalonia.FuncUI.Clone/` MUST NOT be referenced, linked, or
built (`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/AppShell.fs:8`
records the gate). Geometry MUST be expressed as pure projections carrying
no Avalonia type, so every geometry rule is provable headless, exactly as
the existing schematic does
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/Schematic.fs:18`).

0.4 **Single source of commands ‚Äî declared once, surfaced twice.** Two
distinct command surfaces in this spec MUST each be driven from one
declaration, never wired twice:
- the **ribbon ‚Üî drop‚Äëdown menu** pairing (Part D): a command appears in
  both the ribbon and the collapsed‚Äëribbon menus from one definition;
- the **keyboard ‚Üî mouse** pairing (Part E): a command reachable by both a
  key and a mouse gesture declares both bindings on one definition.
Both surfaces MUST read from the centralized command registry of Part E.

0.5 **Schematic, not physical‚Äëgrade.** The on‚Äëtable drawing is a schematic.
Ray bending through tilted elements MUST use a fixed refractive index of
`n = 1.0` outside an element and `n = 1.5` inside, applying Snell's law to
position the drawn lines (Part B). The schematic MUST stay consistent with
which branches the engine beam tree actually computes (reflected /
transmitted), but it MUST NOT attempt physical‚Äëoptics accuracy.

0.6 **Plausible‚Äëexpansion exclusions.** A downstream implementer MUST NOT
add, unless a directive in this spec names it: caching or a retained‚Äëmode
scene graph for the table render; a drawing‚Äëbackend abstraction layer;
schema migration or version‚Äëupgrade code (every install starts from a
blank slate; a schema‚Äëversion mismatch is a validation error, matching
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Storage/schema/optical-constructor-project.schema.json:12`);
a real device/material picker behind the value‚Äëid binding action (Part F
commits only an empty modal); physical‚Äëgrade ray tracing; a third language
beyond the EN/RU resource mechanism (the *mechanism* MUST support adding
one by editing a file, but no third language ships).

0.7 **Net‚Äënew vs reused.** The following are **net‚Äënew** (verified absent
today): element placement (position, the three rotations, bounding box,
normals, drawer), the ray‚Äëgroup model and snapping, the top‚Äëdown table
surface, the ribbon/menu shell, the centralized command model, EN/RU
localization (no `CultureInfo`‚Äëbased localization, `ResourceManager`, or
`.resx` exists; the only `CultureInfo` uses are `InvariantCulture` number
parsing), the standardized‚Äëcontrols module, element groups, and experiment
collections. The following are **reused as‚Äëis**: the beam‚Äëtree solver
(BeamTree.fs:91), the units spine (Units.fs), JSON project storage
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Storage/ProjectFile.fs:20`
`saveProject`, `:31` `openProject`), schema validation
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Storage/SchemaValidation.fs:61`
`validate`), snapshot undo/redo
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Storage/History.fs:20`
`EditHistory`), and the environment/settings store
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/UserEnvironment.fs:141`
`EnvironmentSettings`).

---

## Part A ‚Äî Element geometry, placement & rotation domain model (CRITICAL ‚Äî land first)

### A.0 Problem statement

Today an element on the beam tree (`BeamNode`, BeamTree.fs:53) has no
spatial placement: it carries its kind, its solved `OpticalSystem`, its
incident light, its branch children, and a display unit, but no position,
no orientation, and no bounding geometry. The constructor needs every
element described geometrically ‚Äî a bounding box, two normals, a placement
point, and three rotation angles ‚Äî so it can be drawn on a top‚Äëdown table
and manipulated. This part adds that geometry as a pure, headless‚Äëtestable
domain layer and reserves the schema slots for it. It introduces no
drawing code (Part C) and no ray routing (Part B).

The chosen R1/R2/R3 scheme is dictated by how real optical mounts and
stages are built, not by mathematical convenience; that is why the axes are
modelled exactly rather than as a fixed orthogonal triad.

### A.1 Add an element‚Äëplacement record

A.1.1 A new module `Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Domain/Placement.fs`
MUST define an immutable F# record `ElementPlacement` holding, for one
on‚Äëtable element:
- `placementPoint` ‚Äî the placement point in canonical meters on the table
  plane (see A.2);
- `r1`, `r2`, `r3` ‚Äî the three rotation angles, each carried as the
  engine's `Angle` value so the existing angle constructors are reused, not
  re‚Äëderived;
- `r1Locked`, `r2Locked`, `r3Locked` ‚Äî three independent lock flags;
- `catalogueKind` ‚Äî the UI‚Äëfacing catalogue kind (A.5);
- `valueId : string option` ‚Äî the element value id (A.6);
- `box` ‚Äî the bounding box (A.3);
- `displayUnit : Units.UnitOfMeasure` ‚Äî the element's preferred display unit
  (display metadata only).

A.1.2 `r3Locked` MUST default to `true`; `r1Locked` and `r2Locked` MUST
default to `false` (R3 is locked by default and MUST be deliberately
unlocked before it can change).

### A.2 Placement point is the box centre

A.2.1 The placement point MUST be defined as the centre of the element's
rectangular bounding box. Drawing, snapping (Part B), and slide bounds
(Part E) MUST all treat the placement point as the box centre, never an
edge or corner.

### A.3 Bounding box and the two normals

A.3.1 `Placement.fs` MUST define a `BoundingBox` record with three
canonical‚Äëmeter extents `a1`, `a2`, `b` describing an `A √ó A √ó B` box: a
square `a1 √ó a2` face (with `a1 = a2` for the standard box) extruded by
depth `b` along the primary normal.

A.3.2 The box MUST carry **two normals**:
- **N1 ‚Äî primary normal**, perpendicular to the `A √ó A` face. R1 spins
  about N1 (R1 and N1 coincide by definition).
- **N2 ‚Äî secondary normal**, perpendicular to N1 in the element's rest
  pose.

A.3.3 **Rest pose.** When an element is placed without rotation
(R1 = R2 = R3 = 0), N1 MUST point along the central ray (and so along the
R1 axis) and N2 MUST point along the table normal. An unrotated element
faces the incoming beam squarely.

A.3.4 **Default box proportions by role.** The default box dimensions are a
spec‚Äëauthor detail fixed here (concrete values, canonical meters). They are
guidance for recognisable schematic shapes, not physical dimensions:
- Optical elements (polarizers, sample, lens, mirrors) ‚Äî thin and wide:
  face `A_O = 0.05 m`, depth `B_O = 0.01 m` (`A_O > B_O`).
- Light source ‚Äî long and narrow: face `A_L = 0.025 m`, depth
  `B_L = 0.08 m` (`B_L > A_L`, and `A_O > A_L`, `B_L > B_O`).
- Detector ‚Äî shaped like an optical element: `A_O √ó A_O √ó B_O`.
These defaults MUST live as named constants in `Placement.fs` so a single
edit restyles every element of a role.

### A.4 The three rotations and their frames

A.4.1 **R1** MUST rotate the element about its surface normal N1. At normal
incidence the R1 axis coincides with the central ray; once R2 ‚âÝ 0 the face
no longer faces the beam and the R1 axis is no longer the central ray ‚Äî R1
still turns the element about its own face normal. R1 MUST NOT be treated
as a polarizer's azimuth (a polarizer's azimuth lies *in* the face; at rest
pose it is R2 that corresponds to the azimuth).

A.4.2 **R2** MUST rotate the element about the table normal. R2 is the tilt
that steers a beam within the table plane and is what decouples the R1 axis
from the central ray.

A.4.3 **R2 is measured from the incident ray, not from a fixed table
axis.** When an element sits on a ray that is not horizontal, the element's
own R2 MUST be applied relative to the direction of the incident ray. The
table‚Äëframe rotation of an element whose incident ray already makes angle
`r2` with the horizontal and whose own dialled tilt is `R2` MUST therefore
equal `r2 + R2`. `Placement.fs` MUST expose a pure function that, given the
incident‚Äëray direction and the element's `r2`, returns the element's
table‚Äëframe orientation; this function MUST satisfy the `r2 + R2` additive
law.

A.4.4 **R3** MUST rotate the element about the third box axis (the
`N1 √ó N2` direction). When R3 ‚âÝ 0 the three axes are no longer a fixed
orthogonal triad and **R1 is no longer perpendicular to R2** ‚Äî the
placement math MUST follow the element's mount, not assume orthogonality.

A.4.5 **Per‚Äëaxis lock.** Each rotation MUST be independently lockable and
unlockable, freezing it at its current value. A locked rotation MUST ignore
any change request (Part E rotation gestures are inert while the targeted
axis is locked).

### A.5 Catalogue kind tag

A.5.1 `Placement.fs` MUST define a `CatalogueKind` discriminated union with
exactly the catalogue roles of Part F (Light Source, Linear Polarizer,
Circular Polarizer, Sample, Lens, Flat Mirror, Curved Mirror, Detector).

A.5.2 `Placement.fs` MUST define a pure total function
`toConstructorElement : CatalogueKind -> ConstructorElement` mapping each
catalogue kind to its existing domain case (BeamTree.fs:35): Light Source ‚Üí
`Source`; **both** Linear Polarizer and Circular Polarizer ‚Üí `Polarizer`
(BeamTree.fs:37) ‚Äî a polarizer is a polarizer regardless of placement, and
linear vs circular is a catalogue‚Äëkind distinction, not a new domain case;
Sample ‚Üí `Sample`; Lens ‚Üí `Lens`; Flat Mirror ‚Üí `FlatMirror`; Curved
Mirror ‚Üí `CurvedMirror`; Detector ‚Üí `Detector`. The existing `Analyzer`
case (BeamTree.fs:42) MUST NOT be surfaced as a catalogue kind and MUST be
left untouched (no domain‚ÄëDU removal in this spec).

### A.6 Element value id slot

A.6.1 The `valueId : string option` field (A.1) MUST be present in the
schema and the placement record from the first build, and MUST be `None`
for every element the first build creates. It identifies the concrete
device or material behind an element's role (e.g. which laser an `LS` is,
which material a `Sample` is); the binding of a concrete id is deferred
(Part F commits only the menu action and an empty modal). Reserving the id
now fixes it in the schema so nothing is retro‚Äëfitted later, and it is one
of the drawer's inputs from the start (Part C) so per‚Äëdevice looks can be
added later without rewiring placement or ray logic.

### A.7 Ray‚Äëgroup emission metadata

A.7.1 `Placement.fs` MUST define per‚Äëelement emission metadata recording
whether the element emits its reflected ray group, its transmitted ray
group, or both. The invariant MUST be: an element MAY suppress its
reflected group **or** its transmitted group but **never both** ‚Äî turning
the second one off MUST automatically turn the other back on. This MUST be
enforced by a smart constructor that cannot represent the both‚Äëoff state.

A.7.2 A mirror's default placement MUST suppress transmission (consistent
with the existing mirror rule that a mirror carries the reflected branch
only ‚Äî `BeamNode.attach`, BeamTree.fs:74). Every non‚Äëmirror element MUST be
placed emitting whatever its catalogue kind is configured to emit
(by default both).

### A.8 Schema and project extensions

A.8.1 The project schema
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Storage/schema/optical-constructor-project.schema.json`)
MUST be extended so that placement (the A.1 record, including box, normals
basis, three angles, three lock flags, catalogue kind, value id, emission
metadata, display unit) is representable. The `constructorElement` `$def`
is currently permissive (`true`, schema file `:201`); placement MUST be
added as a sibling of the per‚Äënode element data without renaming any of the
nine reserved anchors (Project.fs:42).

A.8.2 The project aggregate `OpticalConstructorProject` (Project.fs:26)
MUST be extended to carry the table (Part C) and per‚Äëelement placement, so
that an opened project shows every element where it was left. The placement
data MUST round‚Äëtrip through the existing serialization
(ProjectFile.fs:20/:31) and pass schema validation
(SchemaValidation.fs:61) with no new serialization library.

### A.9 Reuse before invention

For angles use the engine's existing `Angle` type and its constructors
rather than introducing a new angle type. For canonical‚Äëmeter values reuse
the `Units` conversions (Units.fs:43/:71). Add placement as a new record in
a new `Placement.fs` module rather than overloading `BeamNode`
(BeamTree.fs:53) with a flag‚Äëheavy spatial payload ‚Äî placement is a
distinct concern from beam‚Äëtree topology.

---

## Part B ‚Äî Ray model, snapping & schematic tracing (CRITICAL ‚Äî land first)

### B.0 Problem statement

The constructor draws the light path as a central ray plus side rays,
snaps elements onto it, re‚Äëaims downstream rays when an element is tilted,
and bends rays schematically through tilted elements. This is the visual
layer; the quantitative result at each element still comes from the
existing beam‚Äëtree solver (BeamTree.fs:91), and the drawn branches MUST
stay consistent with the reflected/transmitted branches the engine
computes (BeamTree.fs:98 `branchEmField`). This part is a pure geometry
layer in a new module
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Domain/RayModel.fs`; it
carries no Avalonia type.

### B.1 Ray group: one central ray and eight side rays

B.1.1 `RayModel.fs` MUST model a ray group as one **central ray (CR)** plus
**eight side rays**. At normal incidence the eight side rays MUST land as
equidistant points on a circle, 45¬∞ apart, with the CR striking the centre
of that circle (the "rifle‚Äëtarget" pattern). The side rays MUST visibly
spread only when a lens, a non‚Äëflat (curved) mirror, a prism, or a wedge
bends them.

B.1.2 The on‚Äëscreen radius of the eight‚Äëray bundle MUST be a fixed fraction
of the element's clear face: `bundle_radius = 0.4 √ó (face_extent / 2)`.
This fraction is a schematic legibility choice (no canonical standard
exists for ray‚Äëbundle radius; it is anchored to the optics rule that a
clear aperture is ‚âà2‚Äì3√ó the beam, so 0.4 keeps all eight side rays clearly
inside the face ‚Äî see References). It MUST be a named constant.

### B.2 Incident, reflected, transmitted groups; detector termination

B.2.1 `RayModel.fs` MUST name the incident ray group (IRG) ‚Äî the ray group
falling on an element ‚Äî as the frame against which that element's rotations
are measured (A.4.3). Every element except a mirror produces both a
transmitted ray group (TRG) and a reflected ray group (RRG); a mirror
produces only an RRG. The drawn groups MUST follow the element's A.7
emission metadata and MUST correspond to the engine branches
(`Reflected`/`Transmitted`, BeamTree.fs:21).

B.2.2 A **Detector (D)** MUST terminate the ray group it receives: no
ray group is drawn leaving a detector.

### B.3 Snapping and downstream travel

B.3.1 Each element's placement point MUST snap onto the central ray
(B.1, A.2). `RayModel.fs` MUST expose a pure function that, given a ray and
a set of elements with their placement points and rotations, produces the
drawn ray geometry with every element snapped to its ray.

B.3.2 Changing an element's R2 and/or R3 MUST change the direction of its
reflected ray R and MAY change the direction of its transmitted ray T.
Everything snapped to a ray downstream of the rotated element MUST travel
with the new ray direction **while preserving all distances** measured
along the ray. Tilting one element MUST therefore drag everything
downstream of it along the new beam direction automatically, keeping the
inter‚Äëelement spacing unchanged.

### B.4 Default light‚Äësource and detector placement

B.4.1 The light source MUST have a default placement near the left side of
the table, vertically centred; the detector MUST have a default placement
near the right side, vertically centred. The central ray MUST originate at
the light source and terminate at the detector, and the initial distance
between them MUST be `2.0 m`, measured along the central ray.

B.4.2 Because everything downstream is snapped to the central ray, moving
the light source MUST drag the whole chain with it. The light source MUST
expose a **position reset** (reachable from its local element menu, Part E)
that returns it to its default spot; when the light source moves or resets,
the remaining elements MUST re‚Äësnap to the ray, preserving their along‚Äëray
distances.

### B.5 Orphaned elements

B.5.1 An element MUST become *orphaned* (left without a ray) only by one of
two operations: (a) changing which ray is tracked (e.g. switching the
tracked branch from T to R), or (b) removing one ray while both R and T are
in use. Elements that were sitting on the removed ray MUST become orphaned.

B.5.2 No other operation MUST orphan an element ‚Äî ordinary rotation and
dragging MUST always keep elements attached to a ray.

B.5.3 If a removed ray is later restored, an orphaned element MUST re‚Äësnap
to it when the restored ray passes within a configured distance of the
element's placement point; otherwise the element MUST stay orphaned until
the user reattaches it. The re‚Äësnap distance MUST be a named, configurable
constant.

### B.6 Schematic Snell tracing through tilted elements

B.6.1 When an element has R2 ‚âÝ 0 and/or R3 ‚âÝ 0, the central and side rays
genuinely change direction and the side rays MAY refract. `RayModel.fs`
MUST compute the bent line geometry by applying Snell's law with `n = 1.0`
outside and `n = 1.5` inside the element (constraint 0.5). These two indices
MUST be named constants in `RayModel.fs`.

B.6.2 When both the reflected and transmitted groups are emitted, the two
MUST be drawn as distinct outgoing groups from the element's face; the
visual distinction (colour / weight / alpha) is specified in Part C.

### B.7 Consistency with the engine

B.7.1 The reflected/transmitted groups the constructor draws MUST be the
same two branches the engine beam tree routes and solves (BeamTree.fs:98,
`:117`). The drawing MUST NOT invent a branch the engine does not compute,
and MUST NOT suppress a branch the element's A.7 metadata emits.

---

## Part C ‚Äî The optical table and top‚Äëdown rendering surface

### C.0 Problem statement

The optical table (OT) is the working surface ‚Äî a top‚Äëdown, drawn‚Äëto‚Äëscale
grey plate on which elements and rays are drawn. The existing
`Schematic.fs` module (Schematic.fs:18) draws a *vertical cross‚Äësection of a
single `OpticalSystem`*; it is a different view and MUST NOT be repurposed
or removed. The constructor's top‚Äëdown surface is net‚Äënew. Its geometry MUST
be a pure projection (constraint 0.3); the FuncUI `Canvas` binding is the
only Avalonia‚Äëaware seam.

### C.1 The plate

C.1.1 A new module `Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Domain/Table.fs`
MUST define an `OpticalTable` record holding the plate's physical width,
length, and thickness in canonical meters, plus a display unit. The default
size MUST be `1.2 m √ó 2.0 m √ó 0.10 m` (width √ó length √ó thickness).

C.1.2 The plate size MUST be editable by the user and MUST be stored with
the project (A.8.2), so a reopened experiment shows the same plate.

C.1.3 The plate MUST be drawn as a grey plate to scale, so elements and
beams sit at true relative scale.

### C.2 View: pan, zoom, rotate, reset

C.2.1 The default view MUST be top‚Äëdown.

C.2.2 **Pan.** Left‚Äëpress + drag on empty table MUST pan the whole table
and every element on it together (elements travel with the table).

C.2.3 **Zoom.** The plain mouse wheel and `Ctrl + wheel` MUST both zoom the
table in and out (honouring the OS‚Äëstandard `Ctrl + wheel = zoom`
convention; this is why R2 is on `Ctrl + Shift + wheel`, Part E).

C.2.4 **Rotate as a view operation.** Rotating the table MUST change only
the viewpoint; all elements travel with it. The table's own R1/R2/R3 MUST
be measured relative to the screen.

C.2.5 **Reset view.** A single action MUST reset the view to (0, 0, 0)
(straight top‚Äëdown) and a sensible default zoom (Part E binds `Ctrl+0` and a
"Reset view" button). This reset is required because the view is easy to
tumble and hard to recover by hand.

C.3 **Table selection.** The table MUST become the selected object whenever
the user clicks anything that is not an optical element. Selecting the table
is how the user steps out of an element to operate on the workspace as a
whole.

### C.4 The drawer

C.4.1 A new module
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/Drawer.fs` MUST define
the drawer as a pure function whose inputs are the element's placement
point, its three rotations, its **element kind**, and its **element value
id** (`None` for the first build), returning pure top‚Äëdown draw geometry
(no Avalonia type). Passing the kind and the value id explicitly from the
start is mandatory so per‚Äërole and (later) per‚Äëdevice/material looks can be
added without rewiring placement or ray logic.

C.4.2 For the first build there MUST be exactly **one standard drawer** used
by every element, drawing the element as a **cylinder**: a visible cylinder
frame with a very light‚Äëgrey, transparent interior so rays passing through
remain visible. Two role‚Äëbased shadings MUST depart from that default: the
light source is drawn in a darker shade; the detector is drawn almost
black, but with its frame still visible so it can be seen and selected.

C.4.3 The drawer MUST offer a **show / hide bounding box** option, off by
default. When on, the box edges MUST make R1/R2/R3 visible at a glance for
inspecting an element's orientation.

### C.5 Drawing weights (schematic conventions)

C.5.1 The schematic MUST follow established optics ray‚Äëdiagram practice:
the central ray is the prominent line (the chief‚Äëray analogue) and the side
rays are lighter (marginal‚Äëray analogue). There is no formal standard for
pixel weights, so the following concrete defaults are fixed here (see
References) and MUST be named constants so a single edit restyles the
schematic:
- central ray: 2.0 px, solid, full opacity;
- side rays: 1.0 px, solid, ~60% opacity;
- reflected group: same hue as the transmitted group at ~35% opacity (it
  carries less energy), so reflected and transmitted read apart at a
  glance;
- element cylinder frame: 1.0 px outline; interior fill light‚Äëgrey at ~15%
  opacity;
- grid lines (if drawn): 1.0 px at ‚â§25% opacity, so the grid never competes
  with geometry.

C.5.2 Colours MUST be chosen for clear on‚Äëscreen visibility and MUST be
expressed as pure colour values the FuncUI binding maps to Avalonia, in the
same style as `SchematicColor` (Schematic.fs:35).

### C.6 Active‚Äëelement clarity

C.6.1 The active element MUST be drawn so that it is unmistakably the active
one (a highlight / halo / selection frame). The active‚Äëelement indicator
MUST be at least 2 px and contrast at least 3:1 against the table
background (WCAG focus‚Äëindicator floor; see References). Acting on the wrong
element silently is the main hazard, so this clarity is a firm requirement,
not a nicety. The exact treatment is a design detail; the clarity is not.

### C.7 Show central ray only, or all rays

C.7.1 The constructor MUST offer an option to show only the CR or the CR
together with all eight side rays. The default MUST be CR‚Äëonly (most
reasoning is on the CR alone; side rays are switched on for focusing or
dispersion). This toggle MUST live on the *Trace / View* ribbon (Part D)
and MUST redraw the table when changed.

### C.8 Reuse before invention

Reuse `SchematicColor` (Schematic.fs:35) as the colour value shape. Do not
fold the top‚Äëdown table geometry into `Schematic.fs` (a different,
cross‚Äësection view); add the new `Table.fs` / `Drawer.fs` / top‚Äëdown layout
modules instead.

---

## Part D ‚Äî Ribbon‚Äëand‚Äëmenu shell and the single command source

### D.0 Problem statement

The main screen needs an Office‚Äëstyle shell: a top menu bar whose top‚Äëlevel
entries each switch a ribbon, and ‚Äî when the ribbon is collapsed ‚Äî the same
entries expand into full drop‚Äëdown menus exposing everything the ribbons
offer. The two are two presentations of one command set; a new command MUST
be declared once and appear in both automatically. The existing shell has a
flat two‚Äëpage nav bar (`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/Shell.fs:73`
`Page`; `:510` `navBar`; `:500` `navButton`); the ribbon shell is net‚Äënew
and is added as the new front door.

### D.1 Ribbon tab set

D.1.1 A new module
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/Ribbon.fs` MUST define
the ribbon as a set of task tabs. The starting tab set MUST be: **Build**
(place elements and groups), **Element** (edit the active element),
**Trace / View** (rays, zoom, table view, reset, show‚ÄëCR toggle),
**Experiment** (groups, collections, detectors), and **Settings**
(language, units, controls, help).

D.1.2 Each ribbon tab's controls MUST be generated from the centralized
command registry (Part E), not hand‚Äëplaced per tab, so a command added to
the registry appears on its tab automatically.

### D.2 Collapsible ribbon ‚Üî full menus

D.2.1 The ribbon MUST be collapsible to reclaim screen space. When
collapsed, the same top‚Äëlevel entries MUST expand into full drop‚Äëdown menus
that expose **everything** the ribbons offer. No command MUST be reachable
only from a ribbon or only from a menu ‚Äî both MUST be projections of the
one command set (constraint 0.4). A command added to the registry MUST
appear in both the ribbon and the menus with no second wiring site.

D.2.2 Office‚Äëstyle multi‚Äëstate collapse (full ribbon ‚Üí titles‚Äëand‚Äëtabs ‚Üí
tabs only) MAY be implemented as a progression but is a design detail, not
a fixed requirement; the firm requirement is the single‚Äësource ribbon‚Üîmenu
equivalence of D.2.1.

### D.3 Contextual element tab

D.3.1 A contextual ribbon tab for the active element MUST appear when an
element is selected and MUST be **appended** beside the persistent tabs
rather than taking over the whole ribbon.

### D.4 Bilingual layout robustness

D.4.1 The ribbon and menus MUST remain legible under both EN and RU
strings, which differ in length (Cyrillic labels tend to run longer). The
layout MUST flex rather than truncate when a label is longer in one
language.

### D.5 Legacy menu entry

D.5.1 A **Legacy** menu entry MUST open the present dockable‚Äëpanel main
screen as‚Äëis (the Construction and Synthesis/Fit pages, `Page` of
Shell.fs:73, laid out by `constructionBody`, Shell.fs:572). The legacy form
is a reference and fallback; it MUST remain reachable and functional but
MUST NOT be required to evolve in lock‚Äëstep with the new screen.

### D.6 The constructor is the front door

D.6.1 The new constructor screen MUST be a top‚Äëlevel page and MUST be the
default landing page when the app starts. The existing `Page` union
(Shell.fs:73) MUST be extended with the constructor page, and the nav /
shell entry MUST be wired through the existing root message path
(`RootMsg`, Shell.fs:121) so navigation stays single‚Äësourced.

### D.7 Reuse before invention

Extend the existing `Page` union (Shell.fs:73) and route through the
existing `RootModel`/`RootMsg` (Shell.fs:94/:121) rather than building a
parallel navigation system. Reuse the dock‚Äëedge seam (`AppShell.toDock`,
AppShell.fs:89) for any docked sub‚Äëpanels of the constructor.

---

## Part E ‚Äî Interaction model: centralized commands, mouse and keyboard

### E.0 Problem statement

The researcher manipulates the active element and the table mostly by mouse
with keyboard accelerators for speed. Where a command is reachable by both
a mouse gesture and a key, the two MUST be one command with two bindings.
Today there is no key‚Äëbinding or command infrastructure to reuse (only
per‚Äëbutton `onClick`); this part introduces the centralized command model
both the ribbon (Part D) and the input handlers read from.

### E.1 The centralized command model

E.1.1 A new module
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/Commands.fs` MUST model
each command as a discriminated‚Äëunion case carrying a small three‚Äëstate
binding ‚Äî **keyboard‚Äëonly**, **mouse‚Äëonly**, or **keyboard‚Äëplus‚Äëmouse** ‚Äî
so a command reachable both ways declares both bindings on one definition.
Every key map and mouse map, and every ribbon/menu control, MUST be derived
from this one registry (constraint 0.4). A new command MUST be added in
this one place.

E.1.2 Every command MUST operate on the **active element** unless it is
explicitly a table or global command.

### E.2 Active‚Äëelement commands (one command per row; both bindings shown together)

The registry MUST declare at least:
- **Open element dialog** ‚Äî double‚Äëclick the element, or right‚Äëclick ‚Üí
  *Element dialog*.
- **Element context menu** ‚Äî right‚Äëclick the element. It MUST expose the
  element's commands directly: Element dialog, Local help, lock/unlock each
  rotation, Reset rotation, toggle reflected/transmitted, Delete,
  Duplicate, turn the element or its group on/off, and (for a detector)
  *Set as primary*.
- **Reset rotation** to (0, 0, 0), with confirmation ‚Äî `Shift+R`, or
  right‚Äëclick ‚Üí *Reset rotation*.
- **Delete element**, with confirmation for a non‚Äëtrivial element ‚Äî
  `Delete` / `Backspace`, or right‚Äëclick ‚Üí *Delete*.
- **Duplicate element** ‚Äî `Ctrl+D`, or right‚Äëclick ‚Üí *Duplicate*;
  **Copy/Paste** ‚Äî `Ctrl+C` / `Ctrl+V`.
- **Local help** for the selected object ‚Äî `F1`, or right‚Äëclick ‚Üí *Local
  help* (Part J).
- **Make next/previous element active** along the beam path ‚Äî `Tab` /
  `Shift+Tab`.

### E.3 Rotations

E.3.1 Each rotation step MUST default to **5¬∞** and MUST be configurable. A
rotation gesture MUST do nothing while its targeted axis is locked (A.4.5).
The registry MUST bind:
- **R1** ‚Äî `Shift + mouse wheel`;
- **R2** ‚Äî `Ctrl + Shift + mouse wheel`;
- **R3** ‚Äî `Alt + mouse wheel` (R3 MUST be unlocked first).

### E.4 Move the active element

E.4.1 **Slide along its ray** ‚Äî `Shift + left‚Äëdrag`, or the arrow keys
(`Shift + arrow` for a larger step). The slide MUST be bounded to the gap
between the element's two immediate neighbours on the ray and MUST NOT pass
either one; left and right slides are the same constrained move in either
direction. Finer placement‚Äëpoint editing MUST be available from the local
element menu (Part E.2 / A).

E.4.2 **Move to a different ray** ‚Äî `Ctrl + left‚Äëdrag` (e.g. off the
transmitted branch onto the reflected one). This is the only gesture that
reassigns an element between rays, distinct from the `Shift` slide.

E.4.3 On **drop**, the table MUST be redrawn, because moving an element may
change where the rays fall.

E.4.4 **Plain left‚Äëdrag on an element MUST do nothing** ‚Äî a deliberate
guard against accidental moves. Because the obvious gesture is inert, the
real gesture (`Shift+drag`) MUST be hinted (cursor change or tooltip when
the pointer is over a movable element).

### E.5 Table and view commands

The registry MUST bind: **Pan** ‚Äî left‚Äëdrag on empty table (C.2.2);
**Zoom** ‚Äî plain wheel or `Ctrl + wheel` (C.2.3); **Reset view** to
top‚Äëdown ‚Äî `Ctrl+0` or the *Reset view* button (C.2.5); **Toggle an element
group** on/off ‚Äî the number keys select the corresponding group (Part G),
alongside the right‚Äëclick toggle.

### E.6 Global commands

The registry MUST bind: **Undo** ‚Äî `Ctrl+Z`; **Redo** ‚Äî `Ctrl+Y` (and
`Ctrl+Shift+Z`), both multi‚Äëlevel (Part K); **Save the project** ‚Äî
`Ctrl+S`; **Close the local menu / pop‚Äëup, or cancel the current drag /
deselect** ‚Äî `Esc`.

### E.7 Drag‚Äëto‚Äëplace from the ribbon

E.7.1 Adding an element MUST be a drag from the *Build* ribbon onto the
table. On mouse release, the new element MUST snap to the middle of the
closest central‚Äëray path at the drop point, so it lands attached to the
nearest beam rather than floating free.

### E.8 Configurability and reuse

E.8.1 The key map MUST be configurable (the rotation step already is), so a
user who prefers different behaviour can change it; the configured key map
MUST persist with the environment settings (Part I / UserEnvironment.fs:141)
. Reuse that settings store rather than adding a parallel preferences file.

---

## Part F ‚Äî Standard element catalogue and value‚Äëid binding placeholder

### F.0 Problem statement

Researchers think in named bench components; the same role can be filled by
different hardware. The catalogue names the roles; the concrete device is a
property (the value id, A.6). The domain already enumerates element kinds
(BeamTree.fs:35).

### F.1 Catalogue names

F.1.1 The catalogue MUST surface these roles, each mapping through
`CatalogueKind.toConstructorElement` (A.5.2): **Optical Table (OT)** (the
workspace itself, Part C), **Light Source (LS)**, **Linear Polarizer (LP)**,
**Circular Polarizer (CP)**, **Sample (S)**, **Lens**, **Flat Mirror**,
**Curved Mirror**, **Detector (D)**. Mirrors, lenses, prisms, and wedges are
the elements that make the side rays meaningful (Part B) and are needed for
focusing and dispersive setups.

F.1.2 A polarizer MUST be just a polarizer regardless of where it sits;
there MUST be no separate "analyzer" catalogue entry and no special label
for a polarizer that follows the sample. The catalogue MUST allow more than
two polarizers in a chain.

### F.2 Value‚Äëid binding action (placeholder)

F.2.1 The element's local menu MUST expose an action to open the value‚Äëid
binding. For the first build this action MUST open a functioning **empty
modal dialog** (a fully working, dismissible modal with no picker content).

F.2.2 The real device/material picker behind that dialog is out of scope
for this spec (constraint 0.6). The committed deliverable is the working
menu action and the working empty modal; this is a complete end state, not
a stub ‚Äî the id slot (A.6) and the menu entry exist so nothing is
retro‚Äëfitted later.

### F.3 Reuse before invention

Map catalogue kinds onto the existing `ConstructorElement` cases
(BeamTree.fs:35) via the A.5.2 function; do not add new element DU cases for
LP/CP (they are `Polarizer`) and do not remove `Analyzer` (BeamTree.fs:42).

---

## Part G ‚Äî Element groups, multiple detectors, and separate storage

### G.0 Problem statement

A researcher runs families of closely related experiments ‚Äî same beam, same
detector, swapping one block at a time ‚Äî and needs to assemble and
re‚Äëassemble them quickly. An element group is the interchangeable block
along the primary central‚Äëray path. The whole point is lossless swapping:
swapping a linear polarizer for a circular one (LP ‚Üî CP) without the
delete‚Äëthen‚Äëre‚Äëadd cycle that loses each element's settings.

### G.1 Group model and member modes

G.1.1 A new module
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Domain/Groups.fs` MUST
define an `ElementGroup` as a named set of member elements, each member
holding its **full configuration** (its placement, rotations, value id,
emission metadata). The group MUST be placeable on, or removable from, the
central‚Äëray path as a unit.

G.1.2 Each group MUST be one of two member modes, chosen per group:
- **Mutually exclusive** ‚Äî at most one member may be in the beam at a time;
  choosing one MUST automatically take the others out of the beam.
- **Multi‚Äëselect** ‚Äî zero, one, or several members may be in the beam at
  once.
Either way the group MUST remember all members and their settings; the
on/off and swap choices MUST change only which members are currently in the
beam, never their stored configuration.

G.1.3 Groups MUST be nameable and reusable, building on the existing
favourites concept (`FavoriteGroup`, UserEnvironment.fs:126) so a commonly
used group can be pinned and dropped back in later.

### G.2 Multiple detectors and the primary one

G.2.1 The primary path normally ends in one detector, but the user MUST be
able to place more than one detector when a branch (e.g. a reflected arm)
needs its own. When there is more than one, the user MUST choose which
detector is the primary one (Part E "Set as primary"). Results and the
headline readout MUST follow the primary detector; secondary detectors MUST
report their own branch independently (consistent with each branch carrying
its own field, BeamTree.fs:98).

### G.3 Separate groups/collections storage

G.3.1 Element groups and experiment collections (Part H) MUST be stored in
their own separate JSON file, kept apart from the per‚Äëproject `.ocproj`
file, so reusable groups and sample‚Äëcentred collections are available
across projects. A new module
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Storage/GroupsLibrary.fs`
MUST own this file's load/save, reusing the shared JSON options and the
schema‚Äëvalidate‚Äëon‚Äëload seam (SchemaValidation.fs:61), with a new schema
file
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Storage/schema/optical-constructor-groups.schema.json`.

G.3.2 The groups/collections file MUST live at a fixed per‚Äëuser
application‚Äëdata path, mirroring the environment store's location
convention (UserEnvironment.fs:279, the `Softellect/Berreman/OpticalConstructor`
app‚Äëdata folder). Because that path is outside the repository working tree,
this file raises no `.gitignore` collision (constraint check satisfied: the
committable‚Äëstate cross‚Äëcheck is moot for an app‚Äëdata file; were it ever
placed in‚Äëtree, a `*.json` name does not collide with any root `.gitignore`
pattern such as `*.cache`/`*.log`/`*.tmp`/`[Bb]in/`/`[Oo]bj/`).

### G.4 Reuse before invention

Reuse the JSON options and validation seam used by the project and
environment stores (SchemaValidation.fs:61; UserEnvironment.fs:185
defaults/load/save pattern) rather than a new serializer; reuse the
`FavoriteGroup` notion (UserEnvironment.fs:126) for pin/reuse.

---

## Part H ‚Äî Experiment collections [Should]

### H.0 Problem statement

An experiment collection is a set of experiments built around the same
sample or samples. It exists to make on/off assembly convenient across the
related experiments and to keep an experiment reproducible when it must be
repeated because conditions changed.

### H.1 Collection model

H.1.1 `Groups.fs` (G.1) MUST define an `ExperimentCollection` as a named
set of experiments sharing the same sample(s), with the user able to turn
elements and groups on and off across the collection. Collections MUST be
stored in the same separate JSON file as groups (G.3) and MUST round‚Äëtrip
through it.

---

## Part I ‚Äî Localization: English and Russian

### I.0 Problem statement

The user base spans EN‚Äë and RU‚Äëspeaking researchers. Localization is
net‚Äënew (constraint 0.7): no localization infrastructure exists today.

### I.1 Centralized, runtime‚Äëread, editable resource

I.1.1 A new module
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/Localization.fs` MUST
load all translatable string pairs from one centralized, human‚Äëeditable
text resource read at run time. The resource MUST be a JSON file
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/strings.json` holding,
per string key, the EN and RU values. An operator or translator MUST be
able to edit the strings, or add a further language, by editing that file ‚Äî
no rebuild required (the file MUST be copied beside the assembly at build,
mirroring how the schema content item is shipped, SchemaValidation.fs:17,
and read from the runtime base directory).

### I.2 Language persisted and restored

I.2.1 The selected language MUST be saved into settings and restored on the
next launch. `EnvironmentSettings` (UserEnvironment.fs:141) MUST be extended
with a `language` field, defaulting to English, and the environment schema
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/optical-constructor-environment.schema.json`)
MUST be extended to match. The language selector MUST live on the *Settings*
ribbon (Part D) and MUST write through the existing save path
(UserEnvironment.fs:302).

### I.3 Startup completeness check with copyable error

I.3.1 At startup the application MUST check the resource for completeness.
If any string is missing for the active language, the app MUST fall back to
the English default for that entry and MUST surface a startup error message
the user can **copy** (so it can be pasted into a bug report or a
translation fix), rather than failing silently or crashing. The startup
check and the copyable error surface MUST be wired in the app entry point
(`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.App/Program.fs`).

### I.4 Language‚Äëneutral scientific notation

I.4.1 Scientific symbols and notation (Œ®, Œî, ¬∞, the unit symbols, R1/R2/R3)
MUST stay language‚Äëneutral and MUST NOT be translated.

### I.5 Reuse before invention

Reuse the `EnvironmentSettings` store (UserEnvironment.fs:141/:302) for the
saved language; reuse the build‚Äëcopied‚Äëcontent‚Äëitem + base‚Äëdirectory read
pattern (SchemaValidation.fs:17) for shipping and reading `strings.json`. Do
not introduce `.resx`/`ResourceManager` (constraint 0.7).

---

## Part J ‚Äî Standardized controls

### J.0 Problem statement

As the interface grows, the maintainer needs visual and behavioural
consistency without hunting through the code. Today CTA colours are
duplicated per view (e.g. `positiveCta`/`negativeCta`, ConstructionView.fs:40).

### J.1 Single control‚Äëflavours module

J.1.1 A new module
`Berreman/OpticalConstructor/OpticalConstructor.Ui/Controls.fs` MUST be the
single place that describes the standard control flavours: a default button,
a primary/accent button, a destructive button, a toggle, and a
numeric‚Äëfield‚Äëwith‚Äëunits. Each flavour MUST be a function the call sites use
instead of styling buttons ad hoc.

J.1.2 When a new flavour is genuinely needed (e.g. a differently coloured
button to stand out), it MUST be added in `Controls.fs` by changing only the
minimum set of properties that distinguish it, rather than styled at the
call site. This is consistency and one‚Äëtouch restyling, not a comprehensive
design system.

### J.2 Reuse before invention

The new constructor views MUST use `Controls.fs` flavours. The existing
`positiveCta`/`negativeCta` (ConstructionView.fs:40) MUST be expressed as
the destructive‚Äëgate flavour in `Controls.fs` so the same‚Äërow Confirm/Cancel
gate (UX commitments, below) draws from one definition.

---

## Part K ‚Äî Undo/redo participation and safety [Must]

### K.0 Problem statement

The constructor needs multi‚Äëlevel undo/redo across element placement,
rotation, locking, group on/off, and detector changes. The engine already
provides multi‚Äëstep whole‚Äëproject snapshot undo/redo (History.fs:20,
`EditHistory`; `:33` `push`; `:39` `undo`; `:47` `redo`); the constructor's
job is to make every constructor action participate.

### K.1 Every constructor action is a snapshot edit

K.1.1 Every constructor model edit that changes the project (placement,
each rotation, each lock toggle, group on/off, swap, detector add/remove,
set‚Äëprimary, table resize, light‚Äësource move/reset) MUST `push` the new
project onto the shared `EditHistory` (History.fs:33), so `Ctrl+Z` /
`Ctrl+Y` (Part E.6) step through them.

K.1.2 Undo and redo MUST be multi‚Äëlevel (History.fs is a multi‚Äëlevel
zipper); the constructor MUST NOT degrade it to single‚Äëlevel.

### K.2 Safety on destructive actions

K.2.1 Destructive or hard‚Äëto‚Äëreverse actions (reset rotation, delete
element, reset view) MUST either be undoable through K.1 or ask for
confirmation, consistent with the `Shift+R`‚Äëwith‚Äëconfirmation behaviour
(Part E.2). Any opposing‚Äëaction pair (Confirm/Cancel) MUST be same‚Äërow with
a visible gap and distinct positive‚ÄëCTA / negative‚ÄëCTA colours (Part J.2 /
ConstructionView.fs:40).

### K.3 Reuse before invention

Reuse `History.fs` (History.fs:20) as the undo/redo carrier; do not add a
command‚Äëpattern diff log or a parallel history.

---

## Operator‚Äëfacing UX commitments

The constructor introduces a new top‚Äëlevel operator page, so the spec
commits explicitly on each checklist point:

1. **Discoverability.** The constructor is a new top‚Äëlevel page and the
   default landing page (D.6); its nav/shell entry is added to the existing
   `Page` union (Shell.fs:73) and marked active with distinct styling like
   the current `navButton` (Shell.fs:500). The *Legacy* entry (D.5) opens
   the existing dockable screen.
2. **Progress granularity.** Feedback MUST be **per‚Äëelement**: selection,
   edits, and re‚Äësnaps reflect on the affected element(s) and the redraw is
   synchronous on drop/edit. The per‚Äënode solve reuses the existing async
   per‚Äënode mechanism (BeamTree.fs:91) at per‚Äëelement granularity; no new
   long‚Äërunning background job with a progress bar is introduced.
3. **Pre‚Äëconfirmation gate.** The constructor dispatches no LLM calls and no
   long‚Äëduration batch work, so a one‚Äëclick interaction model is correct;
   an identify‚Üíconfirm‚Üíprocess scope gate MUST NOT be added. Destructive
   single actions still confirm per K.2.
4. **Completion ‚Üí result‚Äësurface refresh.** When an edit changes the rays
   (rotate, move, group toggle, detector change), the MVU update MUST
   re‚Äërender the table automatically (the FuncUI re‚Äërender path; E.4.3
   redraw‚Äëon‚Äëdrop). A manual reload MUST NOT be required.
5. **Action‚Äëbutton UX.** Opposing actions (Confirm/Cancel on reset/delete)
   MUST be same‚Äërow, with a visible gap and distinct positive/negative
   colours (J.2). Every action that moves or deletes user‚Äëvisible state
   MUST be undoable via `EditHistory` (K.1) ‚Äî the undo affordance, not a
   separate recent‚Äëactions panel.
6. **Committable‚Äëstate under dot‚Äëfolder.** The only new persisted operator
   state is the groups/collections JSON, placed at the per‚Äëuser app‚Äëdata
   path outside the repository (G.3.2), so no `.gitignore` collision is
   possible; `.ocproj` user documents remain committable and are explicitly
   never git‚Äëignored (ProjectFile.fs:14).

**Hidden‚Äëcontrols treatment.** The spec‚Äëwriter's hidden‚Äëcontrols checklist
(LLM‚Äëprofile select, web‚Äësearch‚Äëprovider select, session token counters,
`.specrc.agent` dropdown) does **not apply**: Berreman is an Avalonia F#
desktop application with no `nav.html` and none of those controls. There is
nothing to hide or surface on that axis.

---

## Acceptance criteria

### Part A acceptance
- AC‚ÄëA1: After an element is created with no rotation, `Placement.fs`
  reports N1 along the central ray and N2 along the table normal (rest pose,
  A.3.3), provable headless.
- AC‚ÄëA2: A new element's `r3Locked` is `true` and `r1Locked`/`r2Locked` are
  `false` (A.1.2).
- AC‚ÄëA3: Given an incident ray at angle `r2` and an element with own tilt
  `R2`, the A.4.3 function returns a table‚Äëframe orientation equal to
  `r2 + R2`.
- AC‚ÄëA4: Setting R3 ‚âÝ 0 yields a basis in which R1 is not perpendicular to
  R2 (A.4.4), provable from the placement math.
- AC‚ÄëA5: The emission smart constructor (A.7.1) cannot represent
  reflected‚Äëoff‚Äëand‚Äëtransmitted‚Äëoff simultaneously; turning the second off
  re‚Äëenables the first.
- AC‚ÄëA6: A project carrying placement (box, three angles, three locks,
  catalogue kind, `valueId = None`, emission metadata, display unit)
  round‚Äëtrips through `saveProject`/`openProject` and passes schema
  validation (A.8).
- AC‚ÄëA7: `CatalogueKind.toConstructorElement` maps Linear Polarizer and
  Circular Polarizer both to `Polarizer`, Detector to `Detector`, and never
  to `Analyzer` (A.5.2).

### Part B acceptance
- AC‚ÄëB1: At normal incidence the eight side rays are equidistant points 45¬∞
  apart on a circle of radius `0.4 √ó face_extent/2` with the CR at the
  centre (B.1).
- AC‚ÄëB2: A mirror's drawn groups contain an RRG and no TRG; a non‚Äëmirror
  element with both emissions draws both (B.2.1), consistent with the engine
  branches.
- AC‚ÄëB3: After an element's R2 changes, every downstream element's along‚Äëray
  distance is unchanged while its absolute position follows the new ray
  direction (B.3.2).
- AC‚ÄëB4: A fresh project places the light source left‚Äëmiddle and the
  detector right‚Äëmiddle exactly `2.0 m` apart along the CR; the light‚Äësource
  position reset restores that placement and downstream elements re‚Äësnap
  preserving distances (B.4).
- AC‚ÄëB5: Switching the tracked branch (T‚ÜíR) or removing one of two in‚Äëuse
  rays orphans exactly the elements on the removed ray; restoring the ray
  re‚Äësnaps an orphan iff the ray passes within the configured distance of
  its placement point; no other operation orphans an element (B.5).
- AC‚ÄëB6: A ray crossing an element with R2 ‚âÝ 0 bends per Snell's law with
  `n = 1.0`/`n = 1.5` (B.6), provable headless from `RayModel.fs`.

### Part C acceptance
- AC‚ÄëC1: A new project's table is `1.2 m √ó 2.0 m √ó 0.10 m`; an edited size
  persists and reloads (C.1).
- AC‚ÄëC2: Plain wheel and `Ctrl + wheel` both change zoom; `Ctrl+0` resets
  the view to (0,0,0) and the default zoom (C.2.3, C.2.5).
- AC‚ÄëC3: Clicking empty table selects the table; clicking an element selects
  that element (C.3).
- AC‚ÄëC4: The standard drawer returns cylinder geometry given placement,
  three rotations, kind, and `valueId`; the source shade is darker and the
  detector shade near‚Äëblack with a visible frame (C.4); toggling show‚Äëbounding‚Äëbox
  adds box edges.
- AC‚ÄëC5: The active element's indicator is ‚â•2 px and ‚â•3:1 contrast against
  the table background (C.6).
- AC‚ÄëC6: The show‚ÄëCR‚Äëonly / show‚Äëall toggle defaults to CR‚Äëonly and redraws
  on change (C.7).

### Part D acceptance
- AC‚ÄëD1: The ribbon shows the Build / Element / Trace‚ÄëView / Experiment /
  Settings tabs, each populated from the command registry (D.1).
- AC‚ÄëD2: Collapsing the ribbon exposes every ribbon command through the
  drop‚Äëdown menus, and a command added once to the registry appears in both
  the ribbon and the menus with no second wiring site (D.2.1).
- AC‚ÄëD3: Selecting an element appends a contextual Element tab beside the
  persistent tabs (D.3).
- AC‚ÄëD4: The *Legacy* entry opens the existing dockable Construction /
  Synthesis‚ÄëFit screen (D.5); the constructor is the default landing page
  (D.6).

### Part E acceptance
- AC‚ÄëE1: Every key map, mouse map, and ribbon/menu control derives from the
  one `Commands.fs` registry; a command with both bindings declares them on
  one definition (E.1, constraint 0.4).
- AC‚ÄëE2: `Shift+wheel`/`Ctrl+Shift+wheel`/`Alt+wheel` change R1/R2/R3 by the
  configured step (default 5¬∞) and are inert when the targeted axis is
  locked; R3 requires unlocking (E.3).
- AC‚ÄëE3: `Shift+drag` slides an element along its ray bounded by its
  neighbours and never past them; `Ctrl+drag` reassigns it between rays;
  plain left‚Äëdrag does nothing and shows the movable hint; the table redraws
  on drop (E.4).
- AC‚ÄëE4: Dragging an element from the Build ribbon onto the table drops it
  snapped to the middle of the nearest CR path (E.7).
- AC‚ÄëE5: `Ctrl+Z`/`Ctrl+Y`/`Ctrl+S`/`Esc` perform undo/redo/save/cancel per
  E.6.

### Part F acceptance
- AC‚ÄëF1: The catalogue offers LS, LP, CP, S, Lens, Flat Mirror, Curved
  Mirror, D and no "analyzer" entry; a chain may hold more than two
  polarizers (F.1).
- AC‚ÄëF2: The value‚Äëid binding menu action opens a working, dismissible empty
  modal; no picker content ships (F.2).

### Part G acceptance
- AC‚ÄëG1: A mutually‚Äëexclusive group allows at most one member in the beam
  (choosing one removes the others); a multi‚Äëselect group allows zero/one/
  several; both preserve every member's stored configuration across a swap
  (G.1).
- AC‚ÄëG2: With more than one detector, the user can set the primary; the
  headline readout follows the primary while secondary detectors report
  their own branch (G.2).
- AC‚ÄëG3: Groups and collections round‚Äëtrip through the separate app‚Äëdata
  JSON file with schema validation, independent of any `.ocproj` (G.3).

### Part H acceptance
- AC‚ÄëH1: An experiment collection groups experiments around shared
  sample(s), supports on/off across the collection, and round‚Äëtrips through
  the groups/collections JSON (H.1).

### Part I acceptance
- AC‚ÄëI1: All UI strings resolve through `strings.json` at run time; editing
  the file changes the strings with no rebuild (I.1).
- AC‚ÄëI2: The selected language persists in `EnvironmentSettings` and is
  restored on next launch (I.2).
- AC‚ÄëI3: With a string missing for the active language, the app falls back to
  the English entry and shows a copyable startup error; it neither crashes
  nor fails silently (I.3).
- AC‚ÄëI4: Scientific symbols (Œ®, Œî, ¬∞, R1/R2/R3, unit symbols) are not
  translated (I.4).

### Part J acceptance
- AC‚ÄëJ1: The constructor's buttons/toggles/numeric‚Äëwith‚Äëunits fields are
  produced by `Controls.fs` flavours; a new flavour is added there by
  overriding only the distinguishing properties (J.1).

### Part K acceptance
- AC‚ÄëK1: Each of placement, rotation, lock toggle, group on/off, swap, and
  detector change pushes a snapshot so `Ctrl+Z` reverses it and `Ctrl+Y`
  replays it, across more than one level (K.1).
- AC‚ÄëK2: Reset rotation, delete element, and reset view are each either
  undoable or confirmation‚Äëgated with same‚Äërow distinct‚Äëcolour Confirm/Cancel
  (K.2).

